2026-04-21 01:27:13 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control module switch contacts / series path to load output'] hypothesis_explanation='All modules power correctly and protections behave nominally: the PSU green LED is on, and the control module’s red LED (inverted‑cables indicator) correctly reports that the PSU–control connection is cross‑polarized. This means the control module internally is fine at least up to the indicator network and that the diagnostic LED path is intact. The test on the PSU–control cabling confirmed that the external wiring is simply reversed, not open. \n\nThe load module was then isolated and directly driven with a correct 12 V source in the forward direction of its input diode. The diode showed a normal forward drop (~0.7 V), both lamps showed good continuity, yet neither lamp lit under test. Given intact filaments and a good diode, the only remaining way both lamps can stay dark under a correct 12 V drive is that the series path from the applied positive terminal through the module to the diode/lamp junction is not actually completed in operation – i.e., an open circuit before the diode when the module is connected in the system.\n\nWithin the overall system, that series path is provided by the control module switch and its associated conductors from the control’s positive input to its output. The PSU delivers voltage, but the load never sees it even when the switch is operated. Since the load and its diode are proven good and the external cabling polarity to the load is correct, the remaining likely fault is an internal open circuit in the control module’s switched path (e.g., failed or miswired switch contacts, broken trace, or open joint between the switch and the output terminal). Replacing/repairing the control module’s switch/series output path should restore lamp operation once correct polarity is ensured between PSU and control.'
